	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540561_01.jpg"/>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_orenstein_binyomin">B. Orenstein</persName></p>
			<p>They Were Five</p>
			<p>Very often there were moments in the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2244" type="camp"
					>Hasag Pelcery</placeName>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-508" type="subject">labor camp</term> in <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2170" type="camp">Częstochowa</placeName> when one thought that <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-864" type="subject">Jewish life</term> had been completely
				extinguished.</p>
			<p>The tragic, daily events led to a depressing <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject"
					>condition</term> among <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">the camp inmates</term>.
				Despair, apathy, despondency unwillingly crept into the hearts of the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term><note place="bottom">The words is
					missing in the original.</note> in <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2170" type="camp"
					>Częstochowa</placeName>.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-947" type="subject">political</term> news which reached the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> were often painful and tragic. Every
				attempt at <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-212" type="subject">resistance</term> was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-601" type="subject">put down, suppressed, and decimated</term>. The
					<orgName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/authorities/ehri_cb-438">German military forces</orgName> achieved successes on the
				Eastern Front. Some already lacked courage and patience for the long-enduring Jewish tragedy. In this situation, there were five
				people with a supernatural strength. They had the courage and daring to sing for their ill-fated <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">brothers and sisters</term>, who numbered 6,000 in the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>.</p>
			<p>They were two <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-825" type="subject">women</term> and three <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-826" type="subject">men</term>. With their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">singing</term>, they awoke a ray of hope for the
				future and a longing for the past. The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">songs</term>
				were for the most part sentimental and often called forth tears.</p>
			<p>The five were diverse in terms of repertoire and they <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject"
					>sang</term> in three languages: Yiddish, Hebrew and Polish. <persName ref="#ehri_et_oberman_leon">Leon Oberman</persName> also
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">sang</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">opera</term> arias in Italian.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_nodelberg_roma">Roma Nodelberg</persName> was the most sentimental and often <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">sang</term><q>
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-724" type="subject">My God, My God, Why Have You Forsaken
					Me</term></q>
				<note>Psalm 22</note> and also, in Polish, <q>Harmonia.</q></p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_mardkavitsh_carola">Carola Mardkavitsh</persName> sang <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">folk songs</term>. Her most beloved <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">song</term> was <q>Frimorgen</q>
				<note>Dawn</note>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_oberman_leon">Leon Oberman</persName>, with his Helden Baritone, quickly became known for his high <q>C,</q>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">singing</term> the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">arias</term> from Tosca, Manuela, Ravelo. He also
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">sang</term>
				<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">folk songs</term>,<q>
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-724" type="subject">Lekh-Lekha</term></q>
				<note>Go forth, Genesis 12</note>, <q>Rav Sender,</q> and many others.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_tramkovsky_nehemiah">Nehemiah Tramkovsky</persName> was known for his <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">songs</term>
				<q>Dos fishele</q>
				<note>The little fish</note>, <q>Goles-Lid</q> S<note>ong of the exile</note>, <q><term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-109" type="subject">Yidishe Mame</term></q>
				<note>Jewish mother</note>, <q>Dovidele</q>
				<note>little David</note>, and, completely different, his song <q>Matushka-Tsenstokhova</q>
				<note>Mother Częstochowa</note> was a big hit, <q>I long for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691"
						type="subject">songs</term>, for the brothers and sisters of <placeName
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2170" type="camp">Częstochowa</placeName>.</q></p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_borenstein">Borenstein</persName>, the <placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2170"
					type="camp">Częstochowa</placeName>, Jewish <persName ref="#ehri_et_chaplin_charlie">Charlie Chaplin</persName>, who before the
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1080" type="subject">war</term></p>
			<p><pb n="2" facs="EHRI-ET-YV3540561_02.jpg"/></p>
			<p>acted in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-703" type="subject">films</term>, principally busied himself
				with monologues from <persName ref="#ehri_et_aleichem_sholem">Sholem Aleichem</persName>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_nadir_moshe">Moshe
					Nadir</persName>, <persName ref="#ehri_et_tunkel_yosef">Tunkeler [Yosef Tunkel]</persName>, and others. His monologue
					<q>Gornisht</q>
				<note>Nothing</note> and <q>Boy-material</q>
				<q>Building material</q>, called forth great applause.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-708" type="subject">singing concerts</term> were held in various
				places in the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term>. The biggest and most
				popular hall was the <q>Tzirk</q>
				<q>Circus</q>. It received this name because this was where all those who did not have a place to sleep in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barracks</term> spent the night. There all the
						<q><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-266" type="subject">smuggling</term></q> and <q><term
						ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-933" type="subject">trading</term></q> occurred. The Tzirk was used
				for <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-135" type="subject">concerts</term> and as a <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-758" type="subject">synagogue</term>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-135" type="subject">concerts</term> also took place in <q>Hoffman’s
					shop</q> and in <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-837" type="subject">barracks</term> seven and
				nine.</p>
			<p>The <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-691" type="subject">singing</term> was connected with <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">prayers</term>. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-692" type="subject">singer</term> of <q>Fishele,</q>
				<persName ref="#ehri_et_tramkovsky_nehemiah">Nehemiah Tramkovsky</persName>, was in fact the cantor.</p>
			<p><term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Rosh Hashana</term> and <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Yom Kippur</term> he served as cantor. These were the
				most tragic years for the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> of
					<placeName ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2170" type="camp">Częstochowa</placeName> in the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject">camp</term> of <placeName
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_camps-2244" type="camp">Hasag Pelcery</placeName>, <date when="1943">1943</date>
				and <date when="1944">1944</date>. <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">Prayers</term>
				for the High <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-754" type="subject">Holy Days</term> were held in such
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-831" type="subject">conditions</term> that they are unimaginable. It
				was more like fantasy, yet nevertheless it was a reality. The <q>Tzirk</q> was surrounded by <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-480" type="subject">guards</term>, who had to report if <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1207" type="subject">people</term> could <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">pray</term> or not. Those <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">praying</term> were the ones who left their <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-943" type="subject">work</term> places, left the machines, and came to
					<term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">pray</term>. According the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-1159" type="subject">German</term> conception, this was <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-253" type="subject">sabotage</term> and one would <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-532" type="subject">pay for it</term> with his life. The <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-737" type="subject">prayers</term> were accompanied by tragic crying from
				those present. It is noteworthy that in the same <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-567" type="subject"
					>camp</term> a <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-726" type="subject">wedding</term> took place, and
				the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-693" type="subject">cantor, singer</term>, <persName
					ref="#ehri_et_tramkovsky_nehemiah">Nehemiah Tramkovsky</persName>, conducted the <term
					ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-726" type="subject">wedding ceremony</term> according to Jewish law. It
				took place in Barrack no. 7.</p>
			<p>They were five who <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">sang</term> in the dark, tragic
				moments, <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-694" type="subject">singing</term> away the pain and suffering
				of the Jewish <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-483" type="subject">camp inmates</term> and comforting
				them with the words of the <term ref="https://portal.ehri-project.eu/keywords/ehri_terms-680" type="subject">song</term>: <q>It will
					come once again, and Israel will be happy</q>.</p>
			<p><persName ref="#ehri_et_orenstein_binyomin">Binyomin Orenstein</persName></p>
